","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chesney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Antrim, Down): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (an) tSasanaigh</b>, see   McChesney  .","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Chaney  , a cognate of 3 below.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by or in an oak wood, from Old French <i>chesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (from <i>chesne</i> ‘oak’). Compare   Cheney   2."],"variants":[{"name":"McChesney","meanings":["Scottish (Galloway) and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (an) tSasanaigh</b> ‘son of the Saxon (i.e. the Englishman)’. The spelling seems to represent <i>Mac Shasanaigh</i>, to be pronounced originally as <i>McHasney</i>, rather than the English spelling <i>ch</i>."]},{"name":"Chestnut","meanings":["Scottish (Renfrewshire and Lanarkshire) and northern Irish: altered form of   Chesney  , shortened from   McChesney  . Its assimilation to the English word <i>chestnut</i> is due to folk etymology, the word itself being first recorded in 1519. The surname was probably taken to Ireland at the time of the 17th-century Plantation of Ulster.","English (Norfolk): probably a variant of <b>Chestney</b> (see   Chaney  ), altered by folk etymological association with the word <i>chestnut</i>."]},{"name":"Chesna","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Chesney  ."]}]},{"name":"Adelaide","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin (via French  <b>Adélaïde</b> ), from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heid</i> ‘kind, sort’. It was borne in the 10th century by the wife of the Holy Roman Emperor Otto the Great. She became regent after his death and was revered as a saint. The given name increased in popularity in England during the 19th century, when it was borne by the wife of King William IV; she was the daughter of the ruler of the German duchy of Saxe-Meiningen. The Australian city of Adelaide was named in her honour."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":5,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":15,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":25,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Adelaide Chesney was born in 1081, in Glentham, Lincolnshire, England as the daughter of William de Chesney Lord of Caenby and Glentham. She had at least 3 sons with Osbert de Cundy. She died in 1150, in South Carlton, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1081–1150":"1081–1150","1065–1130":"1065–1130","1104–1169":"1104–1169","1106–1141":"1106–1141","1108–Male":"1108–Surnud","1067–1121":"1067–1121","1121":"1121","10 October 1141":"10. oktoober 1141","1065":"1065","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1081":"1081","1106":"1106","Bef 1130":"enne 1130","1104":"1104","ABT 1121":"umbes 1121","1169":"1169","about 1108":"umbes 1108","1067":"1067","1108":"1108","Thorngate Castle, Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, 